      <title>Styling Jenkins</title>
      <link>http://arlimus.github.io/articles/theming.jenkins/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 24 Oct 2013 02:00:00 +0200</pubDate>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">http://arlimus.github.io/articles/theming.jenkins/</guid>
      <author></author>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Jenkins comes with a nice theming plugin. To use it you need to set up a stylesheet that is accessible to everyone who uses jenkins.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;more&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The plugin will only insert&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;lang-html&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;link rel=&amp;quot;stylesheet&amp;quot; type=&amp;quot;text/css&amp;quot; href=&amp;quot;...&amp;quot; /&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;p&gt;into the page the client receives. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Like many others I decided to use github to serve a CSS file. Unfortunately you can&amp;#39;t just use gists or raw blobs to serve your css, since the mime-time will be &lt;code&gt;text/plain&lt;/code&gt; instead of &lt;code&gt;text/css&lt;/code&gt;. Your browser will ignore it. The solution is to set up a &lt;a href=&quot;http://pages.github.com/&quot;&gt;github page&lt;/a&gt; to serve your css.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have create a theme for my company&amp;#39;s Jenkins:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;magenta.jenkins.png&quot; style=&quot;max-width: 174px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
